excerpt: 351-acre, urban park with botanical gardens, a spring-fed pool, a theater & sports facilities.
detail_description: Zilker Metropolitan Park, a 351-acre urban park in Austin, Texas, is a popular destination named after the generous donor of its land. The park features the iconic Barton Springs Pool and bathhouse, as well as attractions like the Zilker Botanical Gardens and Umlauf Sculpture Garden and Museum. It offers various sports facilities such as soccer fields and a nine-hole golf course.

address: Austin, TX 78746, USA

excerpt: Exhibits, IMAX films & educational experiences aim to tell & interpret the story of Texas.
detail_description: The Bullock Texas State History Museum, established in 2001, is dedicated to interpreting the ongoing narrative of Texas through engaging exhibits, IMAX films, and educational programs. The museum showcases a diverse collection of Texas artifacts from around the world and continuously introduces new displays. By exploring the state's history, visitors can gain a deeper understanding of personal and collective identity while acquiring essential skills.

address: 1800 Congress Ave., Austin, TX 78701, USA

excerpt: Riverlike reservoir for kayaking & rowing, plus trails alongside for jogging & wildlife viewing.
detail_description: Lady Bird Lake, previously known as Town Lake, is a reservoir created along the Colorado River in 1960. The 416-acre lake offers various outdoor activities such as kayaking, rowing, and biking on the Ann and Roy Butler Hike-and-Bike Trail that encircles its banks. Additionally, visitors can enjoy wildlife viewing and jogging along the trails that stretch for miles on both shores.

address: Austin, TX, USA

excerpt: The 1888 granite & marble structure has a significant rotunda & dome, plus House & Senate chambers.
detail_description: The Texas Capitol, a stunning 1888 granite and marble structure, boasts a remarkable rotunda and dome along with House and Senate chambers. Adjacent to this historic site is the Bullock Texas State History Museum, named after Lieutenant Governor Bob Bullock. The museum offers interactive exhibits across three main themes: the founding of Texas, the state's history and name origins, and opportunities within the state.

address: 1100 Congress Ave., Austin, TX 78701, USA

excerpt: 5.1-acre park known for its elevated summit offering sweeping views of Lake Austin.
detail_description: Nestled in a 5.1-acre park, Mt Bonnell is a must-visit destination in Austin, Texas. Named after William Bonnell, this elevated summit stands at 750 feet and offers breathtaking panoramic views of Lake Austin, the city skyline, and the surrounding hills.

address: Austin, TX 78731, USA

excerpt: Austin is the state capital of Texas, an inland city bordering the Hill Country region. name: McKinney Falls State Park
address: 5808 McKinney Falls Pkwy, Austin, TX 78744, USA

This iconic club hosts a variety of live music acts almost every night of the week, featuring genres such as rock, country, jazz, and blues. detail_description: The Cathedral of Junk in Austin is a unique and whimsical multilevel shelter made from over 60 tons of discarded items collected by artist Vince Hannemann since 1989. This quirky construction features various rooms and staircases made from bicycles, televisions, scrap metal, hubcaps, CDs, bicycle wheels, chandeliers, toys, chains and more. The museum hosts annual events such as the Dia de los Muertos commemoration and the Young Latino Artists exhibit. It also collaborates with Mexican institutions to present major cultural works rarely seen outside of Mexico.

address: 419 Congress Ave., Austin, TX 78701, USA

excerpt: Long lines form early for brisket, pulled pork & other smoked meats at this bustling spot.

name: Franklin Barbecue
address: 900 E 11th St, Austin, TX 78702, USA

detail_description: South Congress Bridge, located in downtown Austin, is home to the largest urban bat colony in North America. Every summer night, around 1.5 million Mexican free-tail bats emerge from under the bridge, creating a spectacular sight that attracts hundreds of visitors. The best time to witness this natural phenomenon is at dusk when the bats take flight for their nightly hunt. The view of downtown Austin from the bridge is stunning and adds to the experience of watching the bats in action.
name: Ann W. Richards Congress Avenue Bat Bridge
address: Congress Avenue Bridge, S Congress Ave, Austin, TX 78704, USA

excerpt: Interactive kids' museum with science exhibits, art, indoor & outdoor play spaces & story time.

The museum also includes areas such as the Light Lab, Currents exhibit, and Story Nook, providing diverse experiences for children of all ages.
name: Thinkery

excerpt: Live country music is served up in this hip, upbeat, sprawling honky-tonk with a taco truck outside.

The venue hosts top-notch bluegrass, country-western, and Americana bands on Wednesday nights, attracting enthusiastic dancers showcasing their moves.

detail_description: The Elisabet Ney Museum in Austin, Texas, is a preserved studio and residence of the renowned German artist Elisabet Ney. Despite having the opportunity to live comfortably in Europe, she chose to immigrate to Texas where she sculpted images of Texian heroes. The museum offers educational programs, exhibits, workshops, and lectures throughout the year.
